<p><b>Karma yoga</b> (Sanskrit: कर्म योग), (also known as Buddhi Yoga) or the "discipline of action" is based on the teachings of the <a href="/wiki/Bhagavad_Gita" title="Bhagavad Gita">Bhagavad Gita</a>, a sacred <a href="/wiki/Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a> scripture of <a href="/wiki/Hinduism" title="Hinduism">Hinduism</a>. One of the four pillars of <a href="/wiki/Yoga" title="Yoga">yoga</a>, Karma yoga focuses on the adherence to duty (<a href="/wiki/Dharma" title="Dharma">dharma</a>) while remaining detached from the reward. It states that one can experience salvation (<a href="/wiki/Moksha" title="Moksha">Moksha</a>) or love (<a href="/wiki/Bhakti" title="Bhakti">bhakti</a>) of <a href="/wiki/God" title="God">God</a> by performing their duties in an unselfish manner for the pleasure of the Supreme, which is the welfare of the world. Karma Yoga is an intrinsic part of many derivative types of yoga, such as <a href="/wiki/Natya_Yoga" title="Natya Yoga">Natya Yoga</a>.</p>
